To create a QTextDocument single line in C++, you can use the QTextDocument class in the Qt framework. You can set the plain text content of the document to a single line string using the setPlainText() method. Here is an example:

```
#include <QApplication>
#include <QTextDocument>

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    QApplication app(argc, argv);

    // create a QTextDocument object
    QTextDocument doc;

    // set the plain text content of the document to a single line string
    QString text = "This is a single line QTextDocument.";
    doc.setPlainText(text);

    // print the plain text content of the document to the console
    qDebug() << doc.toPlainText();

    return app.exec();
}
```

This example creates a QTextDocument object, sets the plain text content to a single line string, and prints the plain text content to the console using the toPlainText() method. You can also use QTextCursor to programmatically manipulate the text content of the document.

To create a QTextDocument with rich text content that is limited to a single line in C++, you can set the text using the setHtml() method instead of setPlainText() that we used in the previous example. Here is an example:

